  "prompt": "What is the most abundant rock on earth?",
  "response": "The most abundant rock on Earth is **basalt**. Basalt is a dark-colored, fine-grained igneous rock that forms from the rapid cooling of lava at or near the Earth's surface. It is the primary rock type that makes up the oceanic crust, which covers about 70% of the Earth's surface. Basalt is also found in volcanic regions on continents and is a major component of large igneous provinces, such as the Columbia River Basalt Group in the United States and the Deccan Traps in India.\n\n### Characteristics of Basalt:\n- **Composition**: Basalt is rich in iron and magnesium and primarily composed of minerals such as plagioclase feldspar, pyroxene, and olivine.\n- **Formation**: It forms from the solidification of mafic (magnesium- and iron-rich) magma.\n- **Texture**: Fine-grained due to rapid cooling, though it can contain larger crystals (phenocrysts) in some cases.\n\nWhile basalt is the most abundant rock on Earth's surface, **peridotite**, a dense, coarse-grained ultramafic rock, is the most abundant rock in the Earth's mantle, which makes up the bulk of the planet's volume.",
